semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
\label{lemma Lagrangian tomograph}
	Let $(L_1, L_2)$ be a good pair of Lagrangians in $\hat{W}$. 
	Then, for any $\epsilon >0$ and sufficiently large $d \in \mathbb{N}$, there is a sufficiently small $\delta>0$ and a family of Lagrangians $\{L^s\}_{s \in B_\epsilon^d}$, where $B_\epsilon^d$ is a $d$-dimensional closed ball of radius $\delta$ in the Euclidean space, such that 
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item[(i)] $L_1$ and $L^s$ are Hamiltonian isotopic to each other for all $s \in B_\epsilon^d$, 
		\item[(ii)] $d_H(L_1, L^s) < \frac{\epsilon}{2}$ for all $s \in B^d_\epsilon$, and
		\item[(iii)] $L^s$ and $L_2$ intersect transversely for almost all $s \in B_\epsilon^d$. 
	\end{enumerate}

